The world born of September 11.
NEW YORK – This week marks the 20th commemoration of the 9/11 terrorist attacks in the United States.
On that day, 19 terrorists had taken control of four civilian planes, launched two of the aircraft at the World Trade Center towers in New York, struck the Pentagon with a third, and led to the crash of a fourth plane in Pennsylvania after several passengers physically prevented the terrorists from reaching their target, which many believe was the White House or another U.S. government building in Washington, DC.
All air pirates were from the Middle East, and 15 from Saudi Arabia.
All had been trained in Afghanistan, and four at American flight schools, as part of a planned, organized and conducted operation by Al-Qaïda (the "base"), a terrorist group led by Osama bin Laden.
At the end of the day, 2,977 innocent men, women and children were killed, and more than 6,000 were injured.
Most were Americans, although citizens from over a hundred other countries also lost their lives.
Many at the time feared that 9/11 would usher in an era defined by global terrorism.
Indeed, subsequent attacks carried out by Al-Qaeda followed, including several explosions on Madrid's trains in March 2004, then the attack carried out on London's public transport in July 2005.
The terrorists who had pledged allegiance to the Islamic State (IS) also killed 32 people at Brussels Airport in March 2016, and perpetrated a series of smaller-scale attacks (often using vehicles to ram pedestrians).
However, neither the United States nor any of its allies have ever suffered an attack of comparable scale to those of September 11 – which are without comparison.
It is therefore worth asking: Beyond the immediate losses, what difference has September 11 produced ?
Has history changed and, if so, to what extent ?
Many reasons explain why terrorists have not managed to carry out other major attacks.
After the American invasion of Afghanistan, Al-Qaeda lost its sanctuary.
Almost all governments around the world have put in place control procedures making it harder for potential terrorists to access airports and planes.
The states have significantly strengthened their intelligence, police, and military capabilities in order to minimize risks and counter threats.
They have also developed mutual cooperation, terrorism being one of the rare areas in which states often at odds are eager and willing to work together to a significant extent.
There is now also a broad consensus on what constitutes terrorism – the use of armed force by individuals and groups against civilians for political purposes – as well as a level of support for the principle that governments should not be able to distinguish between terrorists and those who provide them with sanctuary and support.
The time is over when individuals and groups willing to kill in the name of their cause were romanticized as freedom fighters.
It is not a matter of stating that terrorism has stopped claiming the lives of several tens of thousands of people every year.
However, almost all attacks occur in the Middle East, Africa, and South Asia within the framework of current conflicts (mainly in Iraq, Syria, Afghanistan, Libya, Somalia, Nigeria, Pakistan and Yemen), as opposed to isolated attacks, of the 9/11 type, against major powers.
Terrorism is increasingly localized and decentralized.
It is also resilient: the capture or elimination of a terrorist organization leader does not necessarily mean the end of the group.
Al-Qaeda, for example, survived the elimination of Ben Laden by US special forces in Pakistan, nearly ten years after the 9/11 attacks.
It's therefore not surprising that terrorism persists, with no resolution of the problem on the horizon.
The possibility of a new 9/11 cannot be ruled out, although the American government has recently stated that the most urgent terrorist threat to the country exists domestically.
As the Provisional Irish Republican Army formulated after its failed attempt to assassinate British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher in 1984, "Today we haven't had luck, but remember that we just need to have luck once."
You'll always have to.
The danger lies in the fact that one day, terrorists will get their hands on nuclear materials, or will succeed in making and using a biological or chemical weapon, at which point terrorism could determine the era.
For the time being, it is not the case.
The 11 September marked a major historical turning point, with a profound impact on American foreign policy over the past 20 years.
If the attacks did not lead to a global era of terrorism, they certainly spawned the famous war on terror, with major consequences for U.S. behavior around the world, the image of America in the eyes of the world, and the way many Americans ended up viewing their country's foreign policy.
The saga began in Afghanistan.
Soon after the 9/11 attacks, the United States offered the Taliban, who controlled the Afghan government at the time, a choice: hand over the Al-Qaeda leaders on the verge of leaving the country and responsible for organizing the 9/11 attacks, or risk jeopardizing their rule.
After the Taliban had refused to hand over Al-Qaeda leaders, US intelligence and military collaborated with an unstructured confederation of Afghan tribes, called the Northern Alliance, to overthrow the Taliban.
The United States contributed to the formation of a successor government that took control of most of the country.
This control was never, however, total or uncontested.
Many individuals loyal to the Taliban and Al-Qaeda have taken refuge in the neighboring Pakistan, where they have gradually regained strength and resumed their military operations against the government that had replaced them.
On their side, the United States did not sufficiently work to build an Afghan army, reduce corruption, and deprive the Taliban of a sanctuary in Pakistan.
Instead, America reinforced its own presence and military operations in Afghanistan, essentially becoming a key partner to the government in its civil war.
At its peak, US intervention in Afghanistan deployed more than 100,000 American soldiers.
Over more than twenty years, the cost of the operations has risen to over $2 trillion, for more than 2,300 lost American lives, and tens of thousands among the Afghans.
The effort was both excessive and insufficient.
U.S. presence has deprived the Afghan government of much of its legitimacy, and provoked opposition to the United States, while the Taliban have turned out to be more persevering than America, which in 2020 had lost all will to fight in a conflict doomed to end only in an indefinite stalemate.
The global war on terrorism has also led the United States to enter the war in Iraq.
The question remains open as to whether President George W. Bush would have acted militarily if 9/11 had not occurred.
The attacks have certainly reinforced his tendency to want to signal to the world that the United States were not, as President Richard Nixon had formulated it during the Vietnam War, a "powerless and pitiful giant".
This led certain members of the administration (most notably Vice President Dick Cheney) to refuse the risk of seeing terrorists seize massive destructive weapons, which the Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein seemed to possess (which was ultimately not the case) according to most protagonists.
Some were determined to spread democracy in Iraq, and from there across the entire Middle East, believing that this approach was not only achievable, but also would make the region far less likely to produce terrorists and support them.
La war in Iraq, which was triggered in March 2003, did not unfold as the Bush administration and many members of Congress (including Joe Biden, who was a senator at the time) and world leaders had wished or predicted.
The United States were not prepared for the essentials of the events to come.
Military victories won in the first instance have certainly allowed the government to be ousted, but have quickly given way to a widespread agitation as well as a violent civil war.
The decision to dissolve the Iraqi army and exclude many Iraqis associated with the previous regime from government jobs further exacerbated an already chaotic situation.
Fundamentally, Iraq, like Afghanistan, has demonstrated the limits of what military force can accomplish at a reasonable cost and within a reasonable timeframe.
In the end, the United States was forced to bolster its military presence, bringing it close to 170,000 troops, in order to preserve the besieged successor government in Baghdad.
A certain degree of stability has been achieved, but at a considerable cost.
The United States spent at least as much in Iraq as it did in Afghanistan, but at a much heavier human cost: more than 4,000 American soldiers killed, a significantly greater number of wounded, and a skyrocketing rate of suicidal incidents among US military personnel (both in Iraq and Afghanistan).
This total otherwise excludes deaths among private contractors and Iraqis, whose estimates vary widely, but whose number is likely to be several hundred thousand.
The war in Iraq has also weakened the United States in other respects.
No evidence has ever demonstrated Iraq's involvement in the 9/11 attacks, and America's reputation suffered when the argument for a military intervention without UN approval – aimed at removing Saddam's weapons of mass destruction – was found to be based on no real grounds.
Images of American soldiers mistreating Iraqi prisoners have further tarnished the country's reputation.
Meanwhile, war-torn Iraq has become synonymous with an emerging Iran as the region's most powerful country (or one of the two most powerful if Israel is considered).
Since the war, Iran has strengthened its influence over Iraq, Syria, Yemen, and Lebanon.
Iraq and Afghanistan have also proven to be two major strategic distractions.
While the United States intensely involved itself in the Middle East and South Asia, regions lacking great powers present and economic dynamism, the geopolitical balance shifted in favour of the United States, both in Europe and East Asia, due to the emergence of a more aggressive Russia, as well as a stronger and more assertive China.
The world war against terrorism could not and did not provide the United States with a compass in their approach to foreign policy regarding a renewed rivalry between great powers.
The wars waged in the aftermath of September 11 also had significant domestic consequences for the United States.
They shook the confidence in a country that had emerged from the Cold War with historically unparalleled dominant power, and undermined the national unity that had emerged in the immediate aftermath of the attacks.
The costs and failures associated with these wars have, in any case, fueled opposition to a major and lasting world role for the United States, giving rise to a new isolationist trend.
Similarly, this warrior propensity, linked to the 2007-2009 global financial crisis and its economic repercussions, has severely impacted the Americans' confidence in the elites, thus stimulating the rise of a populist sentiment, which, among other consequences, contributed to the arrival of power of Donald Trump.
Today's America is more divided than ever on the domestic front, and less and less disposed to pursue this active form of foreign policy that has characterized it since the end of World War II, and which has largely benefited Americans as well as many others.
With hindsight, we can now look back on September 11 as a harbinger of what was to come: not the globalization of terrorism, but the terrors of globalization.
The attacks sent the message that distance and borders mattered little in the global era.
Nothing stays local for long anymore, whether it's about terrorists born in the Middle East and trained in Afghanistan, or the effects of a global financial crisis that originated from bad US financial management.
We are currently all faced with a pandemic virus that has killed numerous million people since its appearance in China in December 2019.
Wildfires, droughts, floods, storms, and heatwaves that ravage many regions of the world are the consequence of climate change, itself a cumulative effect of human activity releasing unsustainable amounts of greenhouse gases, which trap heat in the atmosphere.
The era begun by recent events comes to a close, marking the 20th anniversary of the US intervention in the country.
Twenty years ago, the Taliban were quickly ousted from power; in the past few weeks, they've regained it just as easily.
It is too early to know if the Taliban will resume their old habits by becoming again a sanctuary for terrorism, and if the world's terrorists will be proud of their victory over America and its allies.
What we know, on the other hand, is that terrorism remains a characteristic of our world.
He will not define the future, but will remain one of the visible facets of a globalization that, for its part, is already determining it.
